The Hellenic Coast Guard rescued 98 migrants from an incident off the coast of Farmakonisi Island, after the migrantsÂ´wooden boat capsized in high winds. 34 bodies were found in the rescue, including 3 infants, 5 girls and 6 boys. 10 adult women and 9 men also lost their lives. The age and gender of one of the dead has not yet been reported. Survivors report another 4 missing. The survivors and one of the deceased children was taken to Leros Island. The other bodies were taken to the island of Rhodes where there are autopsy facilities. A week later, the 99 survivors were transferred to Rhodes Island to assist in the identification of the corpses.

Follow-up 23 September: Austrian police said they have managed to identify some of the 71 decomposing bodies found in a truck on one of the main migration routes from eastern to western Europe in late August. The nine men and one woman of Iraqi origin, all under the age of 50, have been successfully identified, and their relatives have been informed, local police said Wednesday. The bodies of the 59 men, eight women and four children found in a refrigeration truck Aug. 27 were so badly decomposed that none could be identified through photographs or visual inspection, police said. They now hope to be able to identify several others with the help of other methods, including dental records, DNA samples from family members, and precise fingerprints. http://www.4-traders.com/news/Austrian-Police-Identify-Migrant-Truck-Victims--21083074/

column17: 49 migrants were found dead on a ship carrying hundreds of people rescued by the Italian Navy vessel "Cigala Fulgosi" 21 miles off Libya's coast. The bodies of the 49 migrants were discovered by Italian navy officers in the hold of the ship, partially immersed in water and fuel. It is likely the migrants died of asphyxiation due to the fumes coming from the engine. According to early reports, the "Cigala Fulgosi" responded to a distress call and reached the 15-meter-long fishing trawler carrying the migrants, which left Zwara in the night between Friday and Saturday. By the end of operations 313 migrants were rescued, mainly from Morocco, Bangladesh, Pakistan, Sub-Sahara Africa and Syria. Nationalities of the deceased are still being verified. The bodies and survivors were transferred at high sea to the Norwegian vessel "Siem Pilot", which is patrolling the Mediterranean in the framework of the Triton operation.It is unclear if there are still migrants unaccounted for.
